 for bestpractices and # Destination Detail (Reusable Template)

## Overview
Create a premium, editorial Destination Detail page that serves as a reusable template for Roam Resort. The page presents an in-depth narrative about the destination, a large multi-image hero/gallery with lightbox, an experiential content block (dates, guests, amenities, itineraries), host-sourced editorial content, and a clear, inviting CTA to begin the inquiry flow. This page connects to Host Content Management (Listings CRUD) for content creation, editing, previewing, and publishing, and to a Search & Filter system for discovering destinations. It also integrates with the Destination Listings (Browse) page to support discovery and navigation.

Goals:
- Deliver an immersive, editorial destination experience that drives inquiries.
- Provide hosts with robust CRUD capabilities for rich destination listings, including editorial content and image galleries, with draft/publish visibility controls and content validation.
- Offer guests a straightforward discovery path via a browse page and a detailed, persuasive destination page with a prominent CTA to start an inquiry.
- Maintain a cohesive design system aligned with the Roam Resort brand: luxury editorial aesthetic, responsive behavior, and accessible UI.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- Destination Detail (Reusable Template) page: an editorial destination page template focused on in-depth narrative, image gallery, experience details, and a host-sourced content block, plus a CTA to initiate the inquiry flow. Content is sourced primarily from Host Listings CRUD, ensuring editorial control and gallery management.

Goals:
- Convey sense of place through long-form narrative, pull quotes, highlighted experiences, and curated imagery.
- Showcase an immersive hero gallery with lightbox support and a clear visual hierarchy.
- Present an Experience Details Panel including itinerary highlights, suggested dates, guest capacity, amenities, and sample itineraries.
- Provide a Host Info Block with host identity and a contextual note (no direct booking).
- Include a sticky CTA panel encouraging visitors to start the inquiry flow, with microcopy on concierge responsiveness.
- Display Related Destinations (3–4 cards) to support exploration.
- Route guests into the Inquiry Flow, gated by authentication where required.

UI elements and visual guidance:
- Hero Gallery: a responsive, full-width hero with a multi-image slider. Include lightbox for enlarged viewing. Large focal image with smooth transitions between slides.
- Editorial Narrative: long-form content with scalable typography, section headings, pull-quotes, block quotes, and callouts for experiences.
- Experience Details Panel: a clearly delineated panel showing available time ranges, guest capacity, included/excluded amenities, and sample itineraries in digestible cards.
- CTA Panel: a sticky bottom or top CTA labeled “Request a Stay” with secondary microcopy about concierge response times. Include a primary action button in bronze-gold (#A97C50) that remains accessible across scroll.
- Host Info Block: host avatar, name, a short bio, and a contextual note (no direct contact details displayed as standard).
- Related Destinations: 3–4 cards with hero images, destination titles, and key stat lines.

Connected pages and features:
- Destination Listings (Browse): Public list/browse page with search and filters; clicking a destination navigates to Destination Detail.
- Host Content Management (Listings CRUD): Hosts can create/edit/preview/publish listings with editorial content and image galleries. Draft vs. Live visibility controls; content validation on submission.

Visual style alignment:
- Use the Visual Style and Design System provided, including color palette, typography, spacing, and interactive behaviors, ensuring consistency with Roam Resort’s luxury editorial aesthetic.

API integrations:
- No external APIs are required for this prompt, but design should anticipate integration with internal APIs for content retrieval, image assets, and listing status.

## Components to Build
- DestinationDetailPage
  - HeroGallery component: image slides, lightbox, caption area, responsive behavior.
  - EditorialNarrative component: rich text sections, headings, pull-quotes, inline media.
  - ExperienceDetailsPanel component: displays dates suggestion, capacity, amenities, sample itineraries; collapsible sections for details.
  - HostInfoBlock component: avatar, host name, short bio, editorial note.
  - CTAStickyPanel component: sticky CTA with primary action "Request a Stay" and secondary copy about concierge response times.
  - RelatedDestinations component: horizontal card list of 3–4 destination cards.
- ListingsCRUDModule (Host Content Management)
  - ListingForm component: rich editor fields for title, narrative, experience details, image gallery.
  - ImageUpload component: supports multiple images, drag-and-drop, previews, validation.
  - PreviewPanel: real-time preview of editorial content.
  - PublishToggle: Draft / Live visibility control with validation rules.
  - ValidationEngine: ensures required fields, image requirements, content length thresholds.
- SearchAndFilterModule
  - DestinationFilterBar: region, style, keywords; multi-select where applicable.
  - ResultsHint: show count and applied filters.
- DestinationListingsBrowsePage
  - DestinationCard component: image, title, region/style tag, short excerpt, “View Details” action.
  - Pagination / Infinite Scroll logic (with safe defaults).

Technical details:
- Data flows: Content lives in Listings CRUD; DestinationDetail pulls host-edited content via API; search filters query destination listings.
- Media handling: Gallery uses a centralized media store; assets referenced by destination listing IDs.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Use React (or your chosen framework) with TypeScript.
- Ensure runtime safety for all array operations:
  - Guard against null/undefined: const items = data ?? [].
  - Use (Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []) or (items ?? []).map(...)
  - Initialize state as arrays: useState<T[]>([]) and useState<YourType[]>([]).
  - Validate API shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
  - Optional chaining for nested API access: obj?.property?.nested.
- Components must gracefully handle missing data (fallback UI states).
- Accessibility: ensure ARIA labels, contrast ratios per design system, keyboard navigable, and responsive breakpoints.
- State management: use local component state for UI visibility and form state; lift global content state to a centralized store or context if needed.
- Forms: implement controlled inputs with validation and visible error messaging; provide focus management and clear error states.
- Image galleries: implement lazy loading, lazy image placeholders, and accessible lightbox with keyboard navigation.
- Routing: Destination Detail route should accept a destinationId or slug; fetch data with proper loading and error states.
- API integration pattern (internal): mimic endpoints for:
  - GET /destinations?status=live&region=&style=&q=...
  - GET /destinations/:id
  - POST /host/destinations (create)
  - PUT /host/destinations/:id (update)
  - POST /host/destinations/:id/publish (publish)
  - POST /host/destinations/:id/images (upload)
- Rating and micro-interactions: subtle hover states, focus rings in accent color, and smooth transitions for UI elements per design guidelines.

### Backend
- Data models (schema) for Destination Listing:
  - destinations: id, title, slug, region, style, narrative (rich text), editorialContent (structured blocks), experienceDetails (object), hostId, status ('draft' | 'live'), createdAt, updatedAt, publishedAt.
  - images: id, destinationId, url, priority (for gallery order), altText.
  - host: id, name, avatarUrl, bio.
  - inquiries: id, guestId, destinationId, dates, guests, notes, status, createdAt, updatedAt.
- Validation rules:
  - narrative length minimum, content blocks validation, required fields (title, region, style).
  - image gallery must have at least 1 image for published destinations.
  - status transitions: draft -> live only after validation passes.
- Search indexing considerations: region, style, keywords extracted from narrative and metadata for quick search.
- Authorization model:
  - Guests can view published destinations and initiate inquiries.
  - Hosts can create/edit/publish their own listings; read-only access to related inquiries.
  - Admin/Concierge can view all inquiries and update statuses.

### Integration
- Data orchestration:
  - DestinationDetailPage fetches destination data by id/slug; uses a safe data flow with guards for missing data.
  - Host CRUD flows write to destinations and images; upon publish, content becomes visible to guests on DestinationListingsBrowsePage.
  - Search & Filter module queries live destinations and updates the browse results with safeguards for non-array responses.
- Caching and performance:
  - Implement optimistic UI for edits/preview; use debounce for search.
  - Cache frequently accessed destinations on the client with proper invalidation on publish/update.
- Media pipeline:
  - Images stored in a centralized asset store; gallery sum of image URLs with altText.

## User Experience Flow
Guest journey:
1. Lands on Destination Listings (Browse) page; uses search or filters to narrow results.
2. Clicks a published Destination Card to open Destination Detail (Reusable Template).
3. Views hero gallery, reads editorial narrative, and explores experience details.
4. Sees Host Info and related destinations.
5. Encounters sticky CTA panel; clicks “Request a Stay” to begin inquiry flow.
6. Auth flow: if not authenticated, prompted to sign up/log in; upon authentication, stays on/invokes inquiry form.
7. Fills Stay Details form, submits inquiry, receives confirmation.
8. Concierge may send Stripe payment link; host/concierge tracks status via Admin/Concierge panel.

Host journey (Content Management):
1. Logs into Host Dashboard.
2. Creates a new destination listing or edits an existing one.
3. Uploads images, edits editorial content, and configures experience details.
4. Sets Draft or Live status; previews content via PreviewPanel.
5. Saves changes; on Publish, content becomes visible to Guests on the Browse page.

Admin/Concierge journey:
1. Logs into Admin panel.
2. Views all inquiries, updates statuses, adds internal notes.
3. Exports inquiries to CSV as needed.
4. Monitors payment state manually and reconciles offline as required.

## Technical Specifications

Data Models: (Schema highlights)
- destinations
  - id: string
  - title: string
  - slug: string
  - region: string
  - style: string
  - narrative: string (rich text)
  - editorialContent: any (structured blocks)
  - experienceDetails: {
      datesSuggestion: string[]
      guestCapacity: number
      amenities: string[]
      sampleItineraries: string[]
    }
  - hostId: string
  - status: 'draft' | 'live'
  - createdAt: string
  - updatedAt: string
  - publishedAt: string | null
- images
  - id: string
  - destinationId: string
  - url: string
  - altText: string
  - priority: number
- hosts
  - id: string
  - name: string
  - avatarUrl: string
  - bio: string

API Endpoints (suggested patterns)
- GET /destinations?status=live&region=&style=&q=
- GET /destinations/:id
- POST /host/destinations
- PUT /host/destinations/:id
- POST /host/destinations/:id/publish
- POST /host/destinations/:id/images
- GET /inquiries (admin/concierge)
- GET /inquiries/:id
- PATCH /inquiries/:id (status, notes)
- POST /inquiries (guest) - create new inquiry
- POST /inquiries/:id/payments (Stripe link handling, or placeholder for manual)

Security
- Authentication: Guest, Host, Admin roles with role-based access control.
- Authorized routes:
  - Guests: GET destinations, GET destination by id, POST inquiries
  - Hosts: CRUD destinations (create/edit/publish, upload images), view related inquiries (read-only)
  - Admin: View all inquiries, update statuses, export
- Data validation: server-side validation for required fields; server returns structured errors.

Validation
- Client-side and server-side validation:
  - Destination title, region, style required
  - Narrative length minimum thresholds
  - At least one gallery image for live destinations
  - ExperienceDetails fields validated (datesSuggestion non-empty, guestCapacity > 0)
  - Media altText present for accessibility
